00:02:08.580 --> 00:02:16.100
putting forth the items that
we hold, and sharing them

00:02:16.100 --> 00:02:19.130
with the public because
we're sharing them not only

00:02:19.130 --> 00:02:21.260
with you here in this room,

00:02:21.260 --> 00:02:23.870
but as this program
is being webcast.

00:02:23.870 --> 00:02:27.280
We're sharing this program
with the rest of the world

00:02:27.280 --> 00:02:32.240
because those programs
will be put on our screen,

00:02:32.240 --> 00:02:35.290
the screen of the
Library of Congress,

00:02:35.290 --> 00:02:41.000
and are accessible
anywhere around the globe.

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:45.460
So if you have friends,
people you know in Iran,

00:02:45.460 --> 00:02:50.000
or anywhere else,
you can let them know

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:55.650
that we had this program today.

00:02:55.650 --> 00:03:06.020
And this program is on popular
Iranian cinema before the

00:03:06.020 --> 00:03:15.780
revolution, and it is presented
by Doctor Pedram Partovi.

00:03:15.780 --> 00:03:18.880
The importance of this is

00:03:18.880 --> 00:03:22.940
that we do not simply
bring you programs,

00:03:22.940 --> 00:03:27.130
but we bring the scholars who
have studied, who have worked

00:03:27.130 --> 00:03:30.920
on these programs, who can
share their experience,

00:03:30.920 --> 00:03:35.780
their expertise, their
knowledge, their insights

00:03:35.780 --> 00:03:38.500
with all of us to
make the collections

00:03:38.500 --> 00:03:44.260
that we hold better understood,
better appreciated, by everyone.

00:03:44.260 --> 00:03:47.250
And, in a way, this is a role,
the role of this division.

00:03:47.250 --> 00:03:51.170
And the role of all the
divisions in the library.

00:03:51.170 --> 00:03:54.210
This division represents
78 countries.

00:03:54.210 --> 00:03:58.190
We have the whole Middle East
which is rather expansionist

00:03:58.190 --> 00:04:02.350
because we are not limited
by political definitions

00:04:02.350 --> 00:04:06.640
of where we stand, but rather
by linguistic definitions.

00:04:06.640 --> 00:04:12.600
So Persian is spoken not only
in Iran, but much further away.

00:04:12.600 --> 00:04:18.160
And in Afghanistan, in
Tajikistan, and beyond.

00:04:18.160 --> 00:04:24.020
So our region goes
from, you know --

00:04:24.020 --> 00:04:28.600
from the west in Morocco,
and through to the east,

00:04:28.600 --> 00:04:34.950
to Afghanistan, and
northwards to the whole

00:04:34.950 --> 00:04:38.950
of Central Asia,
and the Caucuses.

00:04:38.950 --> 00:04:40.360
This is just the Near East.

00:04:40.360 --> 00:04:43.240
Then we have Africa, and that is
the whole continent of Africa,

00:04:43.240 --> 00:04:45.070
every single country of Africa.

00:04:45.070 --> 00:04:48.670
And then we have the
Hebraic world which is --

00:04:48.670 --> 00:04:53.350
represents not only a
region, not only a place,

00:04:53.350 --> 00:04:56.220
but also the collections
of Hebraic

00:04:56.220 --> 00:04:59.320
and Judaic around the world.

00:04:59.320 --> 00:05:09.490
So with this [inaudible] I will
let my colleague Hirad Dinavari

00:05:09.490 --> 00:05:12.280
introduce the speaker today.

00:05:12.280 --> 00:05:15.250
Hirad.

00:05:15.250 --> 00:05:17.780
&gt;&gt; Hirad Dinavari:
Thank you, Mary Jane.

00:05:17.780 --> 00:05:19.080
Appreciate that.

00:05:19.080 --> 00:05:22.070
Want to thank you all for
coming during the workday.

00:05:22.070 --> 00:05:24.850
I know it's busy
and it's lunch time

00:05:24.850 --> 00:05:29.690
and this is a [inaudible]
lecture opening.

00:05:29.690 --> 00:05:34.330
Essentially every year we do
our Persian book lecture series

00:05:34.330 --> 00:05:38.650
in the Spring period around the
