00:44:07.510 --> 00:44:19.530
[ Foreign Language Spoken ]

00:44:19.530 --> 00:44:22.100
&gt;&gt; Doctor Pedram
Partovi: So I mean the --

00:44:22.100 --> 00:44:25.470
Maybe I want to conclude
here by very briefly talking

00:44:25.470 --> 00:44:29.450
about what these films had
to say about their own times,

00:44:29.450 --> 00:44:32.610
about the many changes that
Pahlavi era social reforms

00:44:32.610 --> 00:44:36.630
and economic programs were
introducing to people's lives.

00:44:36.630 --> 00:44:38.160
Well, this is a very
complicated topic.

00:44:38.160 --> 00:44:40.650
This is a topic that I go in
to in great detail in the book

00:44:40.650 --> 00:44:44.030
that we really can't --
that's very difficult to sum

00:44:44.030 --> 00:44:46.900
up in a brief presentation
like this.

00:44:46.900 --> 00:44:50.730
One thing that I can say is
that Film Farsi and its reliance

00:44:50.730 --> 00:44:54.100
on the cultural past for
its inspiration often stood

00:44:54.100 --> 00:44:56.870
in stark contrast to the
official national culture

00:44:56.870 --> 00:44:59.030
that was being formulated
and promoted

00:44:59.030 --> 00:45:03.070
by modernist intellectuals
and politicians of the time.

00:45:03.070 --> 00:45:04.370
But that's not to suggest

00:45:04.370 --> 00:45:08.070
that these films were somehow
foreshadowing a clerically led

00:45:08.070 --> 00:45:10.860
Islamic revolution
which some have claimed

00:45:10.860 --> 00:45:14.390
to be a wholesale rejection
of the modernization programs

00:45:14.390 --> 00:45:15.900
of the Pahlavi regime.

00:45:15.900 --> 00:45:19.770
I mean almost immediately after
the revolution many of those

00:45:19.770 --> 00:45:21.810
who were involved in the
commercial film industry

00:45:21.810 --> 00:45:24.190
in the Pahlavi era
were themselves banned

00:45:24.190 --> 00:45:27.570
from taking part in the
revolutionary leadership's plans

00:45:27.570 --> 00:45:31.030
for a remaking of
Iranian cinema.

00:45:31.030 --> 00:45:34.850
The revolutionary leadership saw
Film Farsi, ironically enough,

00:45:34.850 --> 00:45:38.800
as a product of the
corrupt Pahlavi era culture.

00:45:38.800 --> 00:45:42.920
And despite the long term
bans on Film Farsi actors,

00:45:42.920 --> 00:45:46.830
on producers, on
directors, fears of a return

00:45:46.830 --> 00:45:50.610
of Film Farsi conventions
and narrative themes

00:45:50.610 --> 00:45:54.520
to the Iranian cinema has become
a vigorous topic of debate

00:45:54.520 --> 00:45:56.660
in media circles
in recent years.

00:45:56.660 --> 00:45:59.210
I mean there are endless
articles published every year

00:45:59.210 --> 00:46:02.040
in the newspapers about
the return of Film Farsi.

00:46:02.040 --> 00:46:05.080
So clearly the ideas of
entertainment at the center

00:46:05.080 --> 00:46:08.690
of the films from the
prerevolutionary period have

00:46:08.690 --> 00:46:09.990
retained their relevance,

00:46:09.990 --> 00:46:12.520
at least among some
Iranian audiences.

00:46:12.520 --> 00:46:15.880
I mean if there's one thing that
we can say about Film Farsi it's

00:46:15.880 --> 00:46:18.480
that it has been and
continues to be part

00:46:18.480 --> 00:46:21.680
of an alternative national
culture to the one offered

00:46:21.680 --> 00:46:23.210
up by ruling elites,
whether we're talking

00:46:23.210 --> 00:46:27.230
about the Pahlavi era or about
the Islamic Republican era.

00:46:27.230 --> 00:46:31.050
And this is really what the book
is about, about how these films,

00:46:31.050 --> 00:46:34.120
in a sense, are formulating,
putting together,

00:46:34.120 --> 00:46:36.750
an alternative national
culture, an alternative idea

00:46:36.750 --> 00:46:42.680
of the nation itself in
contrast to many of the things

00:46:42.680 --> 00:46:45.910
that Pahlavi era elites
at the time were claiming.

00:46:45.910 --> 00:46:48.280
I think I'll stop right there.

00:46:48.280 --> 00:46:51.510
Thank you so much.

00:46:51.510 --> 00:46:55.340
[ Applause ]

00:46:55.340 --> 00:46:57.980
Sure. Yes.

00:46:57.980 --> 00:47:01.770
&gt;&gt; Speaker 2: Doctor
Partovi, thank you very much

00:47:01.770 --> 00:47:03.330
for a wonderful lecture.

00:47:03.330 --> 00:47:06.350
And it's a very fascinating
topic.

00:47:06.350 --> 00:47:10.760
So the question I have for
you is the series of films

00:47:10.760 --> 00:47:17.720
that started to happen late
'70s, things, for example,

00:47:17.720 --> 00:47:21.230
like [inaudible] or [inaudible]
you know, "The Report,"

00:47:21.230 --> 00:47:25.500
and [inaudible] and a number
of things of that sort.

00:47:25.500 --> 00:47:27.220
Some of them are
internationally, you know,

00:47:27.220 --> 00:47:31.520
won awards, but some of them
didn't, but were very different

00:47:31.520 --> 00:47:34.240
in -- from the Film Farsi
commercial tradition.

00:47:34.240 --> 00:47:37.680
How would you categorize that
genre which is really mid

00:47:37.680 --> 00:47:41.000
to late '70s, I think?

00:47:41.000 --> 00:47:42.300
&gt;&gt; Doctor Pedram Partovi: Yeah.

00:47:42.300 --> 00:47:45.640
I mean there is what we might
think of as a kind of realist

00:47:45.640 --> 00:47:49.160
or hyperrealist art
cinema that appears

00:47:49.160 --> 00:47:52.890
in the 1970s in particular.

00:47:52.890 --> 00:47:57.100
Ironically those films are
funded by state organs.

00:47:57.100 --> 00:48:00.230
Doubly ironic is the fact that
most of those films were banned

00:48:00.230 --> 00:48:01.930
from screening in Iran, despite

00:48:01.930 --> 00:48:03.600
that they were funded
by state organs.

00:48:03.600 --> 00:48:08.140
And we have a similar
phenomena after the revolution.

00:48:08.140 --> 00:48:10.450
So I mean many of the
Kiarostami films, for example,

00:48:10.450 --> 00:48:12.980
after the revolution are also
funded by the government,

00:48:12.980 --> 00:48:15.140
but never seen inside
the country.

00:48:15.140 --> 00:48:16.860
At least officially.

00:48:16.860 --> 00:48:18.750
And so yeah.

00:48:18.750 --> 00:48:20.050
I mean it makes you wonder.

00:48:20.050 --> 00:48:22.120
It makes you wonder, "Well, what
is the intended audience here?"

00:48:22.120 --> 00:48:26.330
What is the objective here
behind these particular films?

00:48:26.330 --> 00:48:29.200
And those films were quite
trenchant in their critique

00:48:29.200 --> 00:48:34.430
of social ills in society,
especially one film

00:48:34.430 --> 00:48:38.260
that especially comes to mind
is "Mina's Cycle" which was

00:48:38.260 --> 00:48:44.750
about heroine addiction in Iran
in the prerevolutionary period.

00:48:44.750 --> 00:48:51.230
But yes. I mean those films
at some level were too dark,

00:48:51.230 --> 00:48:55.350
and too depressing, in a sense,
for audiences to go and see

00:48:55.350 --> 00:48:58.610
in large numbers even
if they were allowed

00:48:58.610 --> 00:49:01.010
to be screened in the cinemas.

00:49:01.010 --> 00:49:05.170
I mean these films have tragic
moments, but they're more about,

00:49:05.170 --> 00:49:10.550
in a sense, validating --
reinforcing a particular idea

00:49:10.550 --> 00:49:15.060
of family life that the
modern middle classes

00:49:15.060 --> 00:49:17.360
in the Pahlavi era
believed to be

00:49:17.360 --> 00:49:19.450
at the center of national life.

00:49:19.450 --> 00:49:23.220
And this was, at some level,
in contrast to, at odds with,

00:49:23.220 --> 00:49:27.170
what Pahlavi officials at the
time were trying to claim.

00:49:27.170 --> 00:49:31.090
That what we're trying to create
here is a modern society that's,

00:49:31.090 --> 00:49:34.440
you know, formed on --
along western lines.

00:49:34.440 --> 00:49:38.010
And so the exemplary
citizen is the individual.

00:49:38.010 --> 00:49:41.890
The exemplary citizen is
one that's not beholden

00:49:41.890 --> 00:49:48.580
by family ties that, you know,
drag him down, in a sense.

00:49:48.580 --> 00:49:53.400
I mean this is, you know --
We're very in sociology really

00:49:53.400 --> 00:49:56.300
at its core that becomes crucial

00:49:56.300 --> 00:50:00.120
to the Pahlavi vision
of Iranian society.

00:50:00.120 --> 00:50:03.500
But it's the one that most
people don't buy in to.

00:50:03.500 --> 00:50:05.100
It's one that I'm not
entirely convinced

00:50:05.100 --> 00:50:07.160
that the Pahlavi
regime itself bought

00:50:07.160 --> 00:50:09.280
in to, to be quite honest.

00:50:09.280 --> 00:50:12.180
And so we have these
films that are evidence

00:50:12.180 --> 00:50:13.830
of that, I think in many ways.

00:50:13.830 --> 00:50:16.280
And this is what the draw of
these particular films were,

00:50:16.280 --> 00:50:21.730
more than anything
else, I think.

00:50:21.730 --> 00:50:23.660
Yes? Right.

00:50:23.660 --> 00:50:25.510
Right.

00:50:25.510 --> 00:50:57.920
[ Inaudible ]

00:50:57.920 --> 00:50:59.460
Well, I mean I -- Yeah.

00:50:59.460 --> 00:51:00.760
I mean I think that that

00:51:00.760 --> 00:51:03.090
in itself is also
evidence of the audience.

00:51:03.090 --> 00:51:07.090
With that question, the answer
to that question also feeds

00:51:07.090 --> 00:51:10.240
in to or provides evidence for
the audience of these films.

00:51:10.240 --> 00:51:13.290
I mean many of the people that
were engaged in that cinema,

00:51:13.290 --> 00:51:15.820
were behind the camera,
in a sense were also part

00:51:15.820 --> 00:51:17.700
of the educated middle classes.

00:51:17.700 --> 00:51:20.560
Right. And they were
making films, by and large,

00:51:20.560 --> 00:51:21.860
for the educated middle classes.

00:51:21.860 --> 00:51:23.400
I mean if we think
that, you know --

00:51:23.400 --> 00:51:28.010
Who has the time and
the disposal income,

00:51:28.010 --> 00:51:30.260
for that matter, to go
and watch these movies?

00:51:30.260 --> 00:51:32.520
Certainly not taxi
drivers and porters.

00:51:32.520 --> 00:51:33.940
Right. Right.

00:51:33.940 --> 00:51:40.320
So, as I say, I mean it's --
It may seem strange on its face

00:51:40.320 --> 00:51:42.740
that we don't have middle
class characters, by and large,

00:51:42.740 --> 00:51:46.160
as the central focus of
these particular films,

00:51:46.160 --> 00:51:49.160
but I think that's part of what
I would argue to be the sort

00:51:49.160 --> 00:51:52.310
of counter narrative that
these films are offering

00:51:52.310 --> 00:51:55.750
to the official narrative
of the state at the time.

00:51:55.750 --> 00:51:59.140
That sees, in fact, the
educated middle classes,

00:51:59.140 --> 00:52:00.740
and in particular
the civil servant,

00:52:00.740 --> 00:52:02.950
as the exemplary citizen.

00:52:02.950 --> 00:52:06.410
Well, I defy you to find a civil
servant in any of these films.

00:52:06.410 --> 00:52:07.710
It doesn't exist.

00:52:07.710 --> 00:52:09.010
It doesn't exist.

00:52:09.010 --> 00:52:11.300
I defy you to find a police
presence, for that matter,

00:52:11.300 --> 00:52:12.880
in any of these films.

00:52:12.880 --> 00:52:14.180
They don't exist either.

00:52:14.180 --> 00:52:17.480
You know? I mean it's all street
justice more often than not

00:52:17.480 --> 00:52:19.440
that defines these
particular films.

00:52:19.440 --> 00:52:20.960
So, as I say, I mean it's part

00:52:20.960 --> 00:52:23.220
of the sort of counter
narrative.

00:52:23.220 --> 00:52:26.260
On its face you may
come immediately

00:52:26.260 --> 00:52:29.270
to the assumption that, well,
because it's all about the poor

00:52:29.270 --> 00:52:31.200
and working classes, then
it must be that the poor

00:52:31.200 --> 00:52:33.770
and working classes are watching
these films, but as I say,

00:52:33.770 --> 00:52:37.120
I mean historically
entertainers were

00:52:37.120 --> 00:52:39.290
from the poor and
working classes.

00:52:39.290 --> 00:52:43.150
So it was no different in the
cinema as it was in the theater

00:52:43.150 --> 00:52:45.960
that preceded it in that regard.

00:52:45.960 --> 00:52:48.930
That's why I say, I mean, these
films are very, very much a part

00:52:48.930 --> 00:52:51.040
of Iran's cultural history.

00:52:51.040 --> 00:52:53.240
Right. Oh, yes.

00:52:53.240 --> 00:52:54.540
Absolutely.

00:52:54.540 --> 00:53:02.070
I mean so, for example, the
guy that made this film.

00:53:02.070 --> 00:53:04.750
Right. Absolutely.

00:53:04.750 --> 00:53:08.790
Yeah. I mean so the guy
that directed this film,

00:53:08.790 --> 00:53:13.010
Siamak Yasemi, well, first
of all, he comes from a very,

00:53:13.010 --> 00:53:16.910
very learned Iranian family.

00:53:16.910 --> 00:53:20.030
He spoke several languages,
including Hindi and Urdu.

00:53:20.030 --> 00:53:21.970
He spent many, many
years in India.

00:53:21.970 --> 00:53:25.680
He had a degree, a university
degree, in Persian literature.

00:53:25.680 --> 00:53:28.560
So I mean they know all
of this stuff, in a sense.

00:53:28.560 --> 00:53:31.300
And again that's what makes
all these films so strange,

00:53:31.300 --> 00:53:35.080
as I say, on their face, because
they've been completely ignored.

00:53:35.080 --> 00:53:37.200
They've been seen as
culturally inauthentic,

00:53:37.200 --> 00:53:38.710
but in many ways they're not.

00:53:38.710 --> 00:53:40.610
From my perspective.

00:53:40.610 --> 00:53:43.510
Yeah.

00:53:43.510 --> 00:53:57.370
[ Inaudible ]

00:53:57.370 --> 00:53:58.670
Well, yeah.

00:53:58.670 --> 00:54:01.170
I mean I don't know if there
was some attempt to sort

00:54:01.170 --> 00:54:03.080
of create a national unity

00:54:03.080 --> 00:54:06.860
that the Pahlavi officials
weren't accomplishing.

00:54:06.860 --> 00:54:09.430
As I say, I mean I
think the main reason

00:54:09.430 --> 00:54:11.860
that we have lower class
heroes in these films is

00:54:11.860 --> 00:54:14.140
because historically,
traditionally,

00:54:14.140 --> 00:54:15.440
that's what they were.

00:54:15.440 --> 00:54:17.900
Yeah. I mean again, and
not just the entertainers,

00:54:17.900 --> 00:54:21.330
but I mean most of the
modern social movements

00:54:21.330 --> 00:54:24.880
in Iran have been led by
these kinds of figures too.

00:54:24.880 --> 00:54:27.940
By these lower class figures,
these toughs of the street,

00:54:27.940 --> 00:54:30.570
toughs, the gangsters
of the streets.

00:54:30.570 --> 00:54:33.420
And they've always had this
sort of morally ambiguous role.

00:54:33.420 --> 00:54:38.300
So one day they could be, you
know, clubbing their neighbors

00:54:38.300 --> 00:54:41.760
on the head for protesting
in the streets,

00:54:41.760 --> 00:54:46.610
and the next day they could
be leading the protest.

00:54:46.610 --> 00:54:48.450
So they've always had this
sort of complicated role

00:54:48.450 --> 00:54:50.870
within society, and we see
that in these films too.

00:54:50.870 --> 00:54:53.130
I mean more often than
not we see both poles

00:54:53.130 --> 00:54:59.230
of this [inaudible] character,
the mercenary elements of them

00:54:59.230 --> 00:55:03.490
and of course also the pious and
socially justice minded elements

00:55:03.490 --> 00:55:09.630
of them too or the public
spirited elements of them too.

00:55:09.630 --> 00:55:11.430
Yes?

00:55:11.430 --> 00:55:51.130
[ Inaudible ]

00:55:51.130 --> 00:55:52.970
Well, I mean again -- Right.

00:55:52.970 --> 00:55:55.740
Right. Well, for
the first question,

00:55:55.740 --> 00:55:57.410
in terms of the ratings system,

00:55:57.410 --> 00:56:00.890
there was a very
rudimentary one, we might say.

00:56:00.890 --> 00:56:04.180
I mean films were
rated by country

00:56:04.180 --> 00:56:08.430
of origin at the first level.

00:56:08.430 --> 00:56:12.460
So, you know, if it was a
Western film or European film,

00:56:12.460 --> 00:56:15.190
an American film, only
those films, for example --

00:56:15.190 --> 00:56:17.060
Mostly those films, for example,

00:56:17.060 --> 00:56:20.570
were shown in the
first class theaters.

00:56:20.570 --> 00:56:23.410
And Indian and Iranian
films were, by and large,

00:56:23.410 --> 00:56:26.000
shown in the second and the
third class cinemas generally

00:56:26.000 --> 00:56:27.300
during this period of time.

00:56:27.300 --> 00:56:31.670
So there was a sort of
government ratings system

00:56:31.670 --> 00:56:33.090
for the theaters themselves,

00:56:33.090 --> 00:56:34.620
and that determined how
much they could charge

00:56:34.620 --> 00:56:37.030
for ticket prices and so on.

00:56:37.030 --> 00:56:40.240
So that also explains
the production qualities

00:56:40.240 --> 00:56:41.590
of these particular films too.

00:56:41.590 --> 00:56:44.730
And so they were getting less
in terms of ticket revenues

00:56:44.730 --> 00:56:47.630
and so the films had smaller
budgets than, let's say,

00:56:47.630 --> 00:56:50.360
an American Hollywood
production.

00:56:50.360 --> 00:56:55.500
And then again towards
the 1970s we also get age

00:56:55.500 --> 00:56:57.290
restrictions too.

00:56:57.290 --> 00:57:01.020
So in the 1970s we get
increasingly what we might think

00:57:01.020 --> 00:57:06.320
of as films with, you know,
definite erotic themes,

00:57:06.320 --> 00:57:08.500
sexually suggestive themes.

00:57:08.500 --> 00:57:11.020
Even nudity, for that matter.

00:57:11.020 --> 00:57:13.120
Both Iranian and foreign.

00:57:13.120 --> 00:57:16.810
And yes. There were age
restrictions that were put

00:57:16.810 --> 00:57:20.520
in place to keep people
under the age of 18

00:57:20.520 --> 00:57:23.140
out of those particular
showings.

00:57:23.140 --> 00:57:25.800
But it wasn't quite as
complicated a system

00:57:25.800 --> 00:57:27.100
as we have in the United States.

00:57:27.100 --> 00:57:28.580
And of course I mean
the ratings system

00:57:28.580 --> 00:57:31.600
in the United States really only
dates back to the late 1960s.

00:57:31.600 --> 00:57:32.990
I mean this is not
something that was there

00:57:32.990 --> 00:57:34.550
from the very, very beginning.

00:57:34.550 --> 00:57:38.650
And of course there were always
limits on what you could do,

00:57:38.650 --> 00:57:40.080
especially for Iranian films.

00:57:40.080 --> 00:57:41.680
There was always limits
on what you could do.

00:57:41.680 --> 00:57:45.280
So I mean you couldn't show

00:57:45.280 --> 00:57:49.780
or even stimulate sexual
intercourse on screen.

00:57:49.780 --> 00:57:51.940
Kissing was perfectly
acceptable,

00:57:51.940 --> 00:57:54.090
but I mean if you've seen,
for example, Indian films

00:57:54.090 --> 00:57:55.390
of the same period, even

00:57:55.390 --> 00:57:57.430
that wasn't acceptable
for those films.

00:57:57.430 --> 00:58:02.080
And so at some level
people flocked

00:58:02.080 --> 00:58:03.380
to Iranian films precisely

00:58:03.380 --> 00:58:06.330
because of what the Indian films
didn't show, and people flocked

00:58:06.330 --> 00:58:07.630
to Indian films precisely

00:58:07.630 --> 00:58:08.930
because of what the
Indian films showed

00:58:08.930 --> 00:58:11.690
that the Iranian films
didn't, for that matter.

00:58:11.690 --> 00:58:13.950
So they're sort of working
together in that sense.

00:58:13.950 --> 00:58:16.340
I mean if you watch the Iranian
films you probably watched a lot

00:58:16.340 --> 00:58:18.310
of the Indian films too.

00:58:18.310 --> 00:58:20.910
It was a shared audience in
many ways or at least a lot

00:58:20.910 --> 00:58:23.690
of audience overlap between
these two film forms.

00:58:23.690 --> 00:58:29.270
Was that all of the
questions that you're -- Oh.

00:58:29.270 --> 00:58:31.200
And then post revolution.

00:58:31.200 --> 00:58:32.500
Right. Right.

00:58:32.500 --> 00:58:34.300
Right. Well, no.

00:58:34.300 --> 00:58:36.980
I mean obviously since
the revolution the idea

00:58:36.980 --> 00:58:42.950
of an unrelated man and a woman
sharing any kind of intimacy

00:58:42.950 --> 00:58:47.390
on screen, even touching
one another, is off limits.

00:58:47.390 --> 00:58:49.800
I mean they figured out
ways to get around this.

00:58:49.800 --> 00:58:52.420
So I mean one of my favorites
is I was watching one Iranian

00:58:52.420 --> 00:58:57.140
television show where a son is
coming back from the war front,

00:58:57.140 --> 00:58:59.910
and his mother is sitting
on the couch waiting for him

00:58:59.910 --> 00:59:01.210
to come back from the war front.

00:59:01.210 --> 00:59:02.520
Well, you would imagine the
first thing that they're going

00:59:02.520 --> 00:59:04.000
to do once their son arrives

00:59:04.000 --> 00:59:06.860
at the front door is
hug and kiss each other.

00:59:06.860 --> 00:59:09.150
And they show that.

00:59:09.150 --> 00:59:10.790
But they don't.

00:59:10.790 --> 00:59:16.910
So the scene begins with the
camera pointed at the back

00:59:16.910 --> 00:59:19.360
of the head of the mother
sitting on the couch.

00:59:19.360 --> 00:59:20.930
The doorbell rings.

00:59:20.930 --> 00:59:22.230
She gets up.

00:59:22.230 --> 00:59:23.530
The camera remains stationary.

00:59:23.530 --> 00:59:26.090
But we can hear the interaction.

00:59:26.090 --> 00:59:27.460
We can hear them
kissing each other.

00:59:27.460 --> 00:59:29.520
We can hear them
hugging each other.

00:59:29.520 --> 00:59:30.820
So there are these kinds

00:59:30.820 --> 00:59:33.880
of limitations unfortunately
since the revolution.

00:59:33.880 --> 00:59:35.260
And of course, as
you might imagine,

00:59:35.260 --> 00:59:36.560
these films are completely
banned.

00:59:36.560 --> 00:59:38.790
You cannot watch
these movies legally.

00:59:38.790 --> 00:59:40.090
But that doesn't mean
that people don't.

00:59:40.090 --> 00:59:43.850
I mean by the government's own
admission, something like 70%

00:59:43.850 --> 00:59:47.820
of the population has access
to a satellite television dish.

00:59:47.820 --> 00:59:49.420
Even though that's illegal.

00:59:49.420 --> 00:59:52.050
I'm sorry?

00:59:52.050 --> 00:59:56.350
Well, I mean there are
peddlers in the streets

00:59:56.350 --> 00:59:57.750
that sell these movies.

00:59:57.750 --> 01:00:02.170
Yeah. I mean again you have
these wide honking boulevards

01:00:02.170 --> 01:00:05.090
all over Tehran, and of
course nobody's trying --

01:00:05.090 --> 01:00:06.720
People do try to cross them.

01:00:06.720 --> 01:00:08.770
Pedestrians do try to
cross these streets.

01:00:08.770 --> 01:00:11.040
But you're really taking
your life in to your hands

01:00:11.040 --> 01:00:12.340
if you try to do such a thing.

01:00:12.340 --> 01:00:15.970
So they built all of
these sky bridges that go

01:00:15.970 --> 01:00:18.700
over these boulevards.

01:00:18.700 --> 01:00:22.000
And the peddler sits in the
middle of the sky bridge.

01:00:22.000 --> 01:00:23.620
Nobody sees him.

01:00:23.620 --> 01:00:27.680
And he can sell his wares from
there, and you know thousands

01:00:27.680 --> 01:00:29.670
of people pass him by every day.

01:00:29.670 --> 01:00:34.460
There's a huge sort of
market in underground films.

01:00:36.170 --> 01:00:37.970
Yeah.

01:00:37.970 --> 01:00:47.840
[ Inaudible ]

01:00:47.840 --> 01:00:49.140
Absolutely.

01:00:49.140 --> 01:00:51.020
Yeah. So I mean via satellite
television they're also watching

01:00:51.020 --> 01:00:52.720
these movies.

01:00:52.720 --> 01:00:57.060
There are 1,000 Persian language
satellite networks now set

01:00:57.060 --> 01:01:01.060
up with a couple hundred
dollars and a small studio

01:01:01.060 --> 01:01:04.210
in Los Angeles, in
London, in Dubai,

01:01:04.210 --> 01:01:06.460
and they don't show
the art films.

01:01:06.460 --> 01:01:08.530
They show these films.

01:01:08.530 --> 01:01:11.570
So everybody in Iran knows this
cinema even if they weren't born

01:01:11.570 --> 01:01:16.790
when it was released,
for that matter.

01:01:16.790 --> 01:01:19.470
So yes. I mean despite
the ban, many,

01:01:19.470 --> 01:01:23.960
many people are still
watching these movies.

01:01:23.960 --> 01:01:26.510
Right. Right.

01:01:26.510 --> 01:01:36.360
[ Inaudible ]

01:01:36.360 --> 01:01:39.690
Very few sci fi and monster
for reasons that we've sort

01:01:39.690 --> 01:01:43.170
of talked about because those
films require special effects.

01:01:43.170 --> 01:01:44.560
It's expensive.

01:01:44.560 --> 01:01:46.680
Most of these films
were made with very,

01:01:46.680 --> 01:01:49.360
very little money,
very, very quickly.

01:01:49.360 --> 01:01:52.820
So we don't get much
in the way of sci fi.

01:01:52.820 --> 01:01:55.620
Not much in the way
of horror films.

01:01:55.620 --> 01:01:59.110
We do get -- I mean one of
the genres that sort of pops

01:01:59.110 --> 01:02:03.520
up in the 1950s in the United
States or reappears all

01:02:03.520 --> 01:02:05.600
around the world, an American
genre that reappears all

01:02:05.600 --> 01:02:08.090
around the world, is film noir.

01:02:08.090 --> 01:02:12.140
So we do get some film noir
being made in the 1950s in Iran

01:02:12.140 --> 01:02:14.930
by the director of
this particular film.

01:02:14.930 --> 01:02:18.180
Okay. An Armenian guy by the
name of Samuel Khachikian.

01:02:18.180 --> 01:02:23.330
Okay. And he made a lot of sort
of film noir films in the 1950s.

01:02:23.330 --> 01:02:26.270
So there were sort
of odd attempts made

01:02:26.270 --> 01:02:31.660
by a few characters to
make films along western

01:02:31.660 --> 01:02:33.050
generic lines.

01:02:33.050 --> 01:02:37.420
But, you know, few and
far between, we might say.

01:02:37.420 --> 01:02:40.270
Yeah. Right.

01:02:40.270 --> 01:02:42.510
Exactly. Yeah.

01:02:42.510 --> 01:02:47.220
[ Inaudible ]

01:02:47.220 --> 01:02:51.380
Well, I mean, you know,
sometimes you watch one

01:02:51.380 --> 01:02:54.980
of these movies on the satellite
network in Iran and half

01:02:54.980 --> 01:02:57.140
of the screen is
covered with logos

01:02:57.140 --> 01:03:00.320
because they've taken a bootleg
version of a bootleg version.

01:03:00.320 --> 01:03:02.590
And by the time it gets
down to them, you know,

01:03:02.590 --> 01:03:07.080
you can hardly see what's
going on on screen anymore.

01:03:07.080 --> 01:03:09.380
Yes.

01:03:10.510 --> 01:05:03.980
[ Inaudible ]

01:05:03.980 --> 01:05:06.880
Well, I mean the
middle class is new.

01:05:06.880 --> 01:05:08.980
It's new everywhere in
this part of the world.

01:05:08.980 --> 01:05:11.060
And so how do you
distinguish yourself?

01:05:11.060 --> 01:05:12.360
How do you differentiate
yourself

01:05:12.360 --> 01:05:14.570
from everybody else, in a sense?

01:05:14.570 --> 01:05:16.350
And culture is one way.

01:05:16.350 --> 01:05:18.770
So these movies aren't for us.

01:05:18.770 --> 01:05:21.800
They're -- And you get
this kind of cultural --

01:05:21.800 --> 01:05:23.790
culture of denial precisely
because they're trying

01:05:23.790 --> 01:05:27.020
to differentiate themselves
from their class backgrounds,

01:05:27.020 --> 01:05:29.190
what were once upon a time
their class backgrounds.

01:05:29.190 --> 01:05:30.490
Yes. No doubt.

01:05:30.490 --> 01:05:32.530
No doubt.

